1. INTRODUCTION¶

There has been a lot of research on crime statistics [1] and recent technological advancements have made it lot more easier than ever before to draw insights from extracted crime data using big data analytics [2] which has helped both police and goverment authorities to take the right decisions in order to prevent the ongoing trend from continuing in future [3].

The "Drugs and Guns" project was motivated by this and aims to verify claims made in the "Ross Kemp and the Armed Police" ITV documentary on 6th September, 2018.

The claims were:

  1. Violent crimes are increasing
  2. There are more firearms incidents per head in Birmingham than anywhere else in the UK
  3. Crimes involving firearms are closely associated with drug offenses

These claims were verified by utilizing "All crimes data" which was obtained by merging only "street" files from https://data.police.uk/data/. Since latitudes and longitudes in this dataset were anonymized, "LSOA" and "posttrans" datasets were utilized to decypher the location and include other relevant information required to verify the claims.

The datasets were stored in an Azure container named "lukechugh" and this notebook was run on an Azure instance. The data was stored in Pyspark and Pandas dataframes and were processed with Spark SQL. Storing the data in blob storage was preferred because it is faster than uploading all datasets each time runtime is restarted.

Advantages, disadvantages, and limitations of the chosen visualization, approaches, and statistical methods were explained where possible. The code includes comments and some cells were timed to evaluate efficiency of code. Pandas dataframes were used to convert the Spark dataframe for visualization with seaborn and pyplot.

2.4 DEFINING SCHEMAS AND CREATING DATAFRAMES¶

Dataframes are being produced in this part. To ensure that the appropriate data types were being used, I made the choice to declare the schema structure. Also, the column names are being enforced using the schemas so that I will not have to rename all the columns for all the dataframes. Also, by manual supervision of the CSV files, nullability for some of the columns were set to be true while defining the schemas.

The following schemas were used to insert these files into a dataframe. The header was set to true so that the first line was used as a header . Irrelevant columns were dropped after dataframes with their corresponding schemas were created in order to make queries using them a little faster and make it easier to display them.

In [6]:
all_crimes_schema = StructType(
    [StructField("crime_id", StringType(), True),
     StructField("month", StringType(), False),
     StructField("reported_by", StringType(), False),
     StructField("falls_within", StringType(), False),
     StructField("longitude", DoubleType(), False),
     StructField("latitude", DoubleType(), False),
     StructField("location", StringType(), False),
     StructField("lsoa_code", StringType(), False),
     StructField("lsoa_name", StringType(), False),
     StructField("crime_type", StringType(), False),
     StructField("outcome", StringType(), True),
     StructField("context", StringType(), True),
     ])

posttrans_schema = StructType(
    [StructField("post_code", StringType(), False),
     StructField("long", DoubleType(), False),
     StructField("lat", DoubleType(), False),
     ])

lsoa_schema = StructType(
    [StructField("date", StringType(), False),
     StructField("geography", StringType(), False),
     StructField("geography_code", StringType(), False),

3. DATA EXTRACTION AND FILTERING¶

3.1 REMOVING DUPLICATE ROWS AND TRANSFORMING THE "lsoa_name" & "geography" COLUMN¶

16,279,225 duplicate rows were removed from all crimes. The "lsoa_name" and "geography" columns were transformed to remove alphanumeric substrings like "015C" and "001A" from each lsoa_city/geography. This was necessary to generate larger areas for data to be summed/counted for claim 2. The transformation was achieved using the "trim_lsoa" function, which uses regular expressions to remove the irrelevant substrings and strip empty spaces from the resulting string. This resulted in 349 and 348 unique county names in lsoa_city and geography respectively.

%%time

# defining a function to remove alphanumeric part of substring using regular expression
def trim_lsoa(string):
    return re.sub(r"\d\w","", str(string)).strip()

# defining a udf which will basically work as .apply(function) in python
function = udf(lambda string : trim_lsoa(string), StringType())

# df2 is the all_crimes dataset with transformed lsoa_name column
df2 = df.select("month","longitude","latitude","lsoa_code",function(col("lsoa_name")).alias("lsoa_city"),"crime_type","outcome")

# removing duplicate rows
all_crimes = df2.select("month","longitude","latitude","lsoa_code","lsoa_city","crime_type","outcome").distinct()

3.2 TRANSFORMING THE "post_code" COLUMN¶

To generate larger area to sum up data for claim 2, the "post_code" column was transformed to remove the second part of each postcode. This was done using the "trim_postcode" function, which splits each postcode on the space character and returns only the first part.

In [ ]:
%%time

# Defining a function to split post code on delimeter " " and then return the first part of the post code
def trim_postcode(string):
        return str(string).split(" ")[0]

# defining a udf which will basically work as .apply(function) in python
split_function = udf(lambda string: trim_postcode(string), StringType())

# transforming postcodes
trimmed_posttrans = posttrans.select(split_function(col("post_code")).alias("postcode"),"lat","long")

# posttrans with transformed postcodes
trimmed_posttrans.show(5,False)

3.3 EXTRACTING VIOLENT CRIMES FROM ALL CRIMES AS TIME SERIES¶

The following cell extracts only those instances from all crimes for which crime_type is either "Violent crime" or "Violent and sexual offences". Then total number of violent crimes were counted for each unique month by grouping all the instances by month. The resulting pyspark dataframe is converted to a Pandas DataFrame for time series analysis, with "month" as the index.

In [10]:
%%time

# Filtering all_crimes to have just the violent crimes and counting number of violent crimes that happened in each month
all_crimes.createOrReplaceTempView("all_crimes_table")
violent_crimes_count = spark.sql('''
select
  month,
  count(month) as crimes_commited
from
  all_crimes_table
where
  crime_type = 'Violent crime' or crime_type = 'Violence and sexual offences'
group by
  month
order by
  month
''')

# converting violent_crimes_count pyspark dataframe to pandas dataframe for visualisations
violent_crimes = violent_crimes_count.toPandas()

# converting the month column string datatype to pandas datetime format
violent_crimes.month = pd.to_datetime(violent_crimes.month,format = '%Y-%m')

# setting the datetime formatted month as index of this pandas dataframe
violent_crimes.set_index(violent_crimes.month,inplace=True)

# showing the first 5 rows of the pandas dataframe created
violent_crimes.head()

3.4 PRE-PROCESSING VIOLENT CRIME COUNTS FOR MACHINE LEARNING MODELS¶

In this section, new features with crime counts for the previous 12 months were engineered which enabled ML models to learn the dependency between previous time steps. Nulls were dropped from the resulting dataframe and the "month" column (StringType) was split into two columns "year" and "month", as machine learning models could only work with numbers which is also why data types of the columns were converted to IntegerType.

In [10]:
%%time
w = Window().partitionBy().orderBy(col("month"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("crimes_commited").over(w).alias("lag1"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("lag1").over(w).alias("lag2"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("lag2").over(w).alias("lag3"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("lag3").over(w).alias("lag4"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("lag4").over(w).alias("lag5"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("lag5").over(w).alias("lag6"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("lag6").over(w).alias("lag7"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("lag7").over(w).alias("lag8"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("lag8").over(w).alias("lag9"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("lag9").over(w).alias("lag10"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("lag10").over(w).alias("lag11"))
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select("*", lag("lag11").over(w).alias("lag12"))
violent_crimes_count.select("month","lag1","lag2","lag3","lag4","lag5","lag6","lag7","lag8","lag9","lag10","lag11","lag12","crimes_commited").show()

%%time

# dropping nulls from violent crimes
violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.na.drop()

# This function extracts year from month column by splitting the month column on delimeter "-" and taking the first part (year)
def strip_year(string):
        return str(string).split("-")[0]

# This function extracts month from month column by splitting the month column on delimeter "-" and taking the second part (month)
def strip_month(string):
        return str(string).split("-")[1]

# defining udfs for both extracting year and extracting month which will basically work as .apply(functions)   
extract_year = udf(lambda string: strip_year(string), StringType())
extract_month = udf(lambda string: strip_month(string), StringType())

# creating lagged features of crime counts of previous 12 months so that models can learn time dependency between time steps
splitted_violent_crimes_count = violent_crimes_count.select(extract_year(col("month")).alias("year"),extract_month(col("month")).alias("month"),"lag1",
                                                          "lag2","lag3","lag4","lag5","lag6","lag7","lag8","lag9","lag10","lag11","lag12","crimes_commited")
splitted_violent_crimes_count.show(5,False)

%%time

# changing the data type of all the columns to integer types because models only understand numbers
splitted_violent_crimes_count = splitted_violent_crimes_count.withColumn("year",col("year").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("month",col("month").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("lag1",col("lag1").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("lag2",col("lag2").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("lag3",col("lag3").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("lag4",col("lag4").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("lag5",col("lag5").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("lag6",col("lag6").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("lag7",col("lag7").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("lag8",col("lag8").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("lag9",col("lag9").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("lag10",col("lag10").cast(IntegerType()))\
                                .withColumn("lag11",col("lag11").cast(IntegerType()))\

4. DESIGN, DEVELOPMENT AND REASONING BEHIND USE OF MULTIPLE VISUALISATION METHODS, STATISTICS AND MACHINE LEARNING MODELS¶

Polynomial regression was included in this section for visualising trend, but other models like SARIMAX were not included because they require statistical analysis like the AD-Fuller test before its own implementation and and evaluation measures like RMSE, which are discussed in the next section.

4.1 VIOLENT CRIMES ARE INCREASING, DECREASING OR ARE STABLE ?¶

This section uses different visualisations to analyse trends in violent crimes.

Polynomial Regression

Polynomial regression can model non-linear relationships using a linear model by adding powers of each feature as new features, then training a linear model on these extended set of features. It was used by authors of [4-6] to visualise crime trends in different parts of the world. Most of them used a 3 degree polynomial as it enabled them to approximate the time series by fitting a curve on top of the original time series, which smoothed fluctuations and made it easier to visualise the trend. In this case, a 5 degree polynomial was found to be the best fit for the given time series.

In [11]:
%%time
# setting size of the plot 
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (30,5)
# Linear Regression object 
linreg = LinearRegression()
# Linear Regression can only understand numbers and not pandas datetime formatted months
# There were 126 unique months from 2010-12 and 2021-05, creating dummy months and reshaping it to a matrix
x = np.arange(0,126).reshape(-1,1)
y = violent_crimes.crimes_commited
# Generating 5 degree polynomial features by fitting it on x (dummies for months)
poly_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree=5,include_bias=False)
x_poly = poly_features.fit_transform(x)
# Predicting corresponding y values for 5 degree polynomial x features to make it polynomial regression
linreg.fit(x_poly,y)
y_vals = linreg.predict(x_poly)
# scatter orignal time series data with x as dummy months and y as crime counts
plt.scatter(x,y,color='black')
# plot the fitted 5 degree fitted polynomial with respect to dummy months
plt.plot(x,y_vals,linestyle="--",linewidth=3,color="red",label="Fitted Polynomial")
# replace dummy months with orignal months and only keep the year and the month from pandas datetime format
plt.xticks(np.arange(0,126),violent_crimes.month.apply(lambda x: x.strftime('%Y-%m')),rotation=90)
# setting and formatting title
plt.title("Estimating trend by fitting a 5-degree polynomial",fontsize=20,fontweight="bold")
# setting the legend
plt.legend()
plt.show()

CPU times: user 3.76 s, sys: 471 ms, total: 4.23 s
Wall time: 4.16 s

KDE Plot

A bivariate KDE plot/contour plot depicts the joint probability density between two continuous variables with the use of contour lines which are basically the 2D projections of a 3D bell curve. It was used by authors of [7-10] to determine the crime density in different regions of different countries. Contour lines connect points of equal value and can provide a clear and intuitive visualisation of trends in data by showing how the joint probability density of two continuous variables change over a two-dimensional space. If the contour lines are closely spaced, it could indicate that the probability of the two variables taking on those values is high, while if the contour lines are widely spaced, it could indicate that the probability is low.

In [12]:
%%time
# setting plot size
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (30,5)
# setting title
plt.title("Joint probability density of months and crimes_commited",fontsize=20,fontweight="bold")
# plotting a vertical line indicating the last month in original time series
plt.axvline(x=datetime.strptime("2021-05","%Y-%m"),linewidth=4, color='r',zorder=1,linestyle="--",label="Last month in orignal time series")
# setting up the label
plt.legend()
# plotting bivariate KDE plot
sns.kdeplot(data=violent_crimes, x="month",y="crimes_commited",shade=True,cmap="mako",cbar=True,zorder=2,label="KDE plot")
plt.show()

CPU times: user 667 ms, sys: 123 ms, total: 790 ms
Wall time: 837 ms

Bar Plot

To visualise crime statistics and analyse the trend, the authors of [11-14] implemented barplot as it enabled them to compare all the months based on crime counts. The height of each bar would represent the crime count for different months over time, and the trend in crimes can be seen by comparing the heights of the bars from one month to the next.

%%time

# keeping only the month and year from month column and plotting months vs crime counts using barplot

Moving Average Plot

A moving average plot is computed by calculating the rolling mean over a window size of certain months. Some of the authors of [15-17] used window size of 3 months whereas others used window size of 12 months to compute the rolling mean as it smooths out fluctuations, separates out random variations, and is less prone to false signals which makes it much more easier to illustrate overall pattern in data and visualise the underlying trend. As a result, one can expect to see a line chart with the average value of the data plotted at each point in time.

In [14]:
%%time
# defining function for plotting moving average
def plot_moving_average(timeseries, title):
    plt.clf()
    # computing rolling mean of window size of every 12 months
    rolmean = pd.Series(timeseries).rolling(window=12).mean() 
    # setting figure size
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30, 5))
    # setting and formatting title
    plt.title("Moving Average",fontsize=20,fontweight="bold")
    # plotting orignal time series
    ax.plot(timeseries, label= title,color='green')
    # plotting rolling mean
    ax.plot(rolmean,label='Moving Average',linestyle="--",linewidth=3,color="red")
    # plotting title
    plt.title("Analysing trend using Moving Average",fontsize=20,fontweight="bold")
    # setting legend
    ax.legend()
    plt.show()

pd.options.display.float_format = '{:.8f}'.format
plot_moving_average(violent_crimes['crimes_commited'],'Orignal time series')

<Figure size 2160x360 with 0 Axes>
CPU times: user 311 ms, sys: 1.8 ms, total: 313 ms
Wall time: 323 ms

Interpretations:

Unlike other visualisations, KDE plot forecasted the joint probability density beyond the last month (red line) in given time series. All four visualisations explicitly show that as we move along the x axis in the direction of future months, the crime counts increase. Overall, there has been an increasing trend from 2010-12 to 2021-05, verifying claim 1 to be true. However, from 2019 to 2021 the trend has been almost stable.

5. SELECTION APPLICATION AND REASONING BEHIND USE OF STATISTICAL ANALYSIS AND MULTIPLE EVALUATION MEASURES¶

5.1 SEASONALITY¶

The detrended time series was grouped by all values for each month and year, averaged to compute the seasonal component for that year, and replicated for all years in the original time series to obtain the seasonality.

In [17]:
%%time
# setting figure size
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (30,5)
# decomposing the orignal time series
decomposition = sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose(violent_crimes['crimes_commited'], model='additive',extrapolate_trend='freq')
# taking only the seasonal component from decomposition
seasonal = decomposition.seasonal
# setting and formatting title
plt.title("SEASONALITY", fontsize = 24, fontweight = 'bold')
plt.plot(seasonal)
plt.show()

CPU times: user 282 ms, sys: 1.6 ms, total: 283 ms
Wall time: 321 ms

The plot indicates that the given time series has a seasonal component that repeats every 12 months and also shows that given time series has additive seasonality because the height and width of seasonal component doesn't changes with time. Since given time series has both a trend and seasonality, it is not stationary.

5.2 RESIDUALS¶

A time series is assumed to be comprised of only trend and seasonality, so any other signals are considered as residuals which are obtained by removing the trend and seasonality from the original time series.

In [18]:
%%time
# picking up only residuals from time series decomposition
residuals = decomposition.resid
# setting and formatting title
plt.title("RESIDUALS", fontsize = 24, fontweight = 'bold')
plt.plot(residuals)
plt.show()

CPU times: user 274 ms, sys: 789 µs, total: 275 ms
Wall time: 278 ms

5.3 AUGMENTED DICKY-FULLER TEST [18]¶

Statistical models assume stationarity and their performance depends on this assumption which is why the given time series was made stationary by detrending and double differencing. It was detrended by subtracting the rolling mean and then dividing by rolling standard deviation of 12 months window. Then it's stationarity was tested using the augmented Dickey-Fuller test which is a hypothesis test where the null hypothesis is that the given time series is not stationary. If the test statistic is less than the critical value, we can reject the null hypothesis and say with confidence that the time series is stationary.

In [10]:
%%time
# This cell shows that time series successfuly became stationary by detrending and double differencing

# detrending the time series by subtracting the rolling mean and dividing it by rolling standard deviation
y = violent_crimes['crimes_commited']
y_detrend =  (y - y.rolling(window=12).mean())/y.rolling(window=12).std()

# detrending and double differencing the time series to make it stationary
y_12lag_detrend =  y_detrend - 2*y_detrend.shift(12)

# defining a function to perform augmented dicky fuller test
def ADF_test(timeseries, dataDesc):
    print(' > Is the {} stationary ?'.format(dataDesc))
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries.dropna(), autolag='AIC')
    print('Test statistic = {:.3f}'.format(dftest[0]))
    print('P-value = {:.3f}'.format(dftest[1]))
    print('Critical values :')
    for k, v in dftest[4].items():
        print('\t{}: {} - The data is {} stationary with {}% confidence'.format(k, v, 'not' if v<dftest[0] else '', 100-int(k[:-1])))

# H0: Null hypothesis states that data is not stationary
# H1: Alternate Hypothesis states that data is stationary
ADF_test(y_12lag_detrend,'12 lag differenced de-trended data')

	10%: -2.5821223452518263 - The data is  stationary with 90% confidence
CPU times: user 11.8 ms, sys: 2.05 ms, total: 13.9 ms
Wall time: 58.9 ms

Since the test statistic is lower than the critical value for 1%, we can reject the null hypothesis and say that the data is stationary with 99% confidence.

5.4 MODEL TRAINING AND EVALUATION¶

In this section models are being built to learn patterns in the given time series so that they can forecast the crime counts for the future. The ability of these models to forecast is evaluated qualitatively by plotting forecasted crime counts on top of orignal crime counts and quantitatively by computing RMSE between forecasted crime counts and orignal crime counts. Reason for using RMSE for evaluating regression-based models was that it penalizes forecasts that are far from the actual values more than those that are closer. RMSE was normalized by dividing it by the difference between the maximum and minimum values in the test data to account for the large scale of the values.

5.4.1 SARIMAX [19]¶

Authors of [19-21] implemented SARIMAX to forecast crimes in different parts of the world because SARIMAX can model the next step in the sequence as a linear function of the differenced observations and residual errors, and can recognize the influence of adjacent points in time on one another. Also since, given time series had seasonality SARIMAX seemed appropriate for this use case.

5.4.2 FINDING OPTIMAL VALUES FOR ORDER AND SEASONAL ORDER¶

The stationary time series was split into train and test sets, and the optimal values for the order and seasonal order parameters were determined by looking for those combinations for which Akaike Information Criterion [22] is the least.

In [ ]:
%%time
# dropping nulls from lagged detrended time series
y_12lag_detrend = y_12lag_detrend.to_frame().dropna()
# creating test, train and validation sets
y_to_train = y[:'2020-01-01'] 
y_to_test = y['2020-02-01':]  

# Trying every single combination for p,d,q and P,D,Q with respect to AIC score to find the optimal values 
# for order and seasonal order
p = d = q = range(0, 4)
seasonal_period = 12
pdq = list(itertools.product(p, d, q))
seasonal_pdq = [(x[0], x[1], x[2],seasonal_period) for x in list(itertools.product(p, d, q))]
for param in pdq:
    for param_seasonal in seasonal_pdq:
        try:
            mod =\
            sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(y_to_train,
                                      order=param,
                                      seasonal_order=param_seasonal,
                                      enforce_invertibility=False)
            results = mod.fit(disp=False)
            print('ARIMA{}x{}12 - AIC:{}'.format(param, param_seasonal, results.aic))
        except Exception as ex:
            continue

5.4.3 TRAINING SARIMAX¶

SARIMAX was trained using the order and seasonal order obtained from previous cell and then model's result diagnostics were plotted.

In [12]:
%%time
order = (2, 1, 3)
seasonal_order = (3, 1, 2, 12)
# Fitting the model and plot the model diagnostics
model = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(y_to_train,
                            order=order,
                            seasonal_order=seasonal_order,
                            enforce_invertibility=False)
results = model.fit(disp=False)
results.plot_diagnostics(figsize=(15, 12))
plt.show()

CPU times: user 10.9 s, sys: 7.69 s, total: 18.6 s
Wall time: 10.4 s

The result diagnostics in this section shows that the residuals were stationary and normally distributed, indicating that SARIMAX fitted well on the training data.

5.4.4 EVALUATING SARIMAX¶

To evaluate SARIMAX, predictions were made for the next 16 months to match months in test data. Then normalised RMSE was computed between the predicted mean of the forecasted crime counts and the actual crime counts in the test data.

In [13]:
%%time
# Produce the forcasted tables to match the months in test data
pred_uc = results.get_forecast(steps=16)
pred_ci = pred_uc.conf_int()
pm = pred_uc.predicted_mean.reset_index()
pm.columns = ['Month','Predicted_Mean']
pci = pred_ci.reset_index()
pci.columns = ['Month','Lower Bound','Upper Bound']
final_table = pm.join(pci.set_index('Month'), on='Month')
final_table

5.4.5 RANDOM FORESTS [23]¶

Authors of [23-26] used Random Forests to forecast crimes in different parts of the world reason being that random forests trains multiple decision trees in parallel on random samples of the training data (bootstrapping) and produces an output by averaging the results of all trees in the forest which makes it less likely to overfit. Another advantage of Random Forest is that bootstrapping makes it robust to outliers and underperformance of any tree doesn't affect the overall performance.

In [ ]:
%%time
# using vector assembler to create a single feature which contains values of all other features
vecAssembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=['year','month','lag1','lag2','lag3','lag4','lag5','lag6','lag7',
                                          'lag8','lag9','lag10','lag11','lag12'], outputCol="features")

# Splitting the whole pre-processed dataset into 80% train and 20% test data
(trainDF, testDF) = splitted_violent_crimes_count.randomSplit([.8, .2])
# defining random forests model with inputs as features and labels
rf = RandomForestRegressor(featuresCol="features",labelCol='crimes_commited')
# creating pipeline of vector assembler and random forest model
pipeline = Pipeline(stages=[vecAssembler, rf])
# fitting pipeline on training data
model = pipeline.fit(trainDF)
# making predictions
rf_predDF = model.transform(testDF)
# defining evaluator with rmse as the filter
Evaluator = RegressionEvaluator(predictionCol="prediction",labelCol="crimes_commited",metricName="rmse")
# finding the maximum number of crimes commited in test data
rmse = Evaluator.evaluate(rf_predDF)
# finding the maximum number of crimes commited in test data
max_in_test = rf_predDF.agg({'crimes_commited': 'max'}).rdd.flatMap(lambda x: x).collect()
# finding the minimum number of crimes commited in test data
min_in_test = rf_predDF.agg({'crimes_commited': 'min'}).rdd.flatMap(lambda x: x).collect()
# finding normalised RMSE for Random Forest
print(f"Normalised RMSE is {rmse/(max_in_test[0] - min_in_test[0]):.2f}\n")

Normalised RMSE is 0.09

CPU times: user 8.55 s, sys: 1.14 s, total: 9.69 s
Wall time: 25min 12s
In [ ]:
# converting pyspark dataframe to pandas dataframe
rf_pred = rf_predDF.toPandas()
# parsing year and month as strings and concatenating them to form the xticks
rf_pred.time = rf_pred.year.astype("str") + "-" + rf_pred.month.astype("str")
# setting figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(30,5))
# setting and formatting the title
plt.title("Random Forest's Predictions vs Actual crimes commited",fontsize=20,fontweight="bold")
# setting and formatting the x label 
plt.xlabel("Month",fontsize=20,fontweight="bold")
# setting and formatting the y label
plt.ylabel("Crime Counts",fontsize=20,fontweight="bold")
# rotating the xticks by 90 degrees so that they wont merge with each other
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
# plotting the original crimes commited in test data
plt.plot(rf_pred.time,rf_pred.crimes_commited, label = "Orignal Crimes Counts",linewidth=3,color='b')
# plotting the predicted crimes commited
plt.plot(rf_pred.time,rf_pred.prediction, label = "Predicted Crime Counts",linewidth=3,color='r',linestyle='--')
# setting up the legend
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Both the line plot and Normalised RMSE of 0.09 indicate that this model performed really well at predicting crime counts for unseen data. Indicating that it's a good fit

5.4.6 GBDT [27]¶

Authors of [27-30] used Gradient boosted decision trees for forecasting crimes because GBDTs train several decision trees sequentially, with each tree trying to improve its predecessor by learning from predecessor's mistakes/residuals which is somewhat similar to what statistical models do.

In [13]:
%%time
# using vector assembler to create a single feature which contains values of all other features
vecAssembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=['year','month','lag1','lag2','lag3','lag4','lag5','lag6','lag7',
                                          'lag8','lag9','lag10','lag11','lag12'], outputCol="features")

# Splitting the whole pre-processed dataset into 80% train and 20% test data
(trainDF, testDF) = splitted_violent_crimes_count.randomSplit([.8, .2])
# defining gradient boosted decision tree model with inputs as features and labels
gbt = GBTRegressor(featuresCol="features",labelCol='crimes_commited')
# creating pipeline of vector assembler and GBDT model
pipeline = Pipeline(stages=[vecAssembler, gbt])
# fitting pipeline on training data
model = pipeline.fit(trainDF)
# making predictions
GBDT_predDF = model.transform(testDF)
# defining evaluator with rmse as the filter
Evaluator = RegressionEvaluator(predictionCol="prediction",labelCol="crimes_commited",metricName="rmse")
# evaluating predictions
rmse = Evaluator.evaluate(GBDT_predDF)
# finding the maximum number of crimes commited in test data
max_in_test = GBDT_predDF.agg({'crimes_commited': 'max'}).rdd.flatMap(lambda x: x).collect()
# finding the minimum number of crimes commited in test data
min_in_test = GBDT_predDF.agg({'crimes_commited': 'min'}).rdd.flatMap(lambda x: x).collect()
# finding normalised RMSE for GBDT
print(f"Normalised RMSE is {rmse/(max_in_test[0] - min_in_test[0]):.2f}\n")

Normalised RMSE is 0.07

CPU times: user 9.99 s, sys: 1.3 s, total: 11.3 s
Wall time: 28min 4s

Both the line plot and Normalised RMSE of 0.07 indicate that this model performed really well at predicting crime counts for unseen data. Indicating that it's a good fit. Both Random Forest and GBDT performed similar to each other and were better than SARIMAX in terms of both time taken and normalized RMSE.

5.5 ARE THERE MORE FIREARM INCIDENTS PER HEAD IN BIRMINGHAM THAN ANYWHERE ELSE IN THE U.K. ?¶

The following 3 queries are executed:

  1. First cell sums up the total number of residents for each geography in the geography_residents table
  2. Second cell counts the total number of firearm incidents for each lsoa_city in the firearm_count table
  3. Third cell counts the firearm incidents per head for each lsoa_city and arranges them in descending order in the firearms_per_head table

The first row of the firearms_per_head table shows the region with the most firearm incidents per head.

In [28]:
%%time
firearm_incidents.createOrReplaceTempView("firearm_incidents_table")
lsoa.createOrReplaceTempView("lsoa_table")

# This query counts the population of each geography 
geography_residents = spark.sql(''' 
select
  geography,
  sum(total_residents) as total_residents
from
  lsoa_table
group by
  geography
order by
  geography
''')

# showing first 20 rows of the geography_residents dataframe

In [30]:
%%time
# This query returns the firearm incidents per head arranged in descending order
geography_residents.createOrReplaceTempView("geography_residents_table")
firearm_count.createOrReplaceTempView("firearm_count_table")
firearms_per_head = spark.sql(''' 
select
  fct.lsoa_city as REGION,
  fct.firearm_count,
  grt.total_residents,
  fct.firearm_count / grt.total_residents as INCIDENTS_per_HEAD
from
  geography_residents_table as grt
  inner join firearm_count_table as fct on grt.geography = fct.lsoa_city
order by
  INCIDENTS_per_HEAD desc
''')

# Since firearms_per_head was ordered by incidents_per_head in descending order, the first row indicates the maximum
firearms_per_head.show(20,False)

5.6 ARE FIREARM INCIDENTS CLOSELY ASSOCIATED WITH DRUG OFFENCES ?¶

The following cell involves 3 queries:

  1. The first cell counts the number of drug offenses that happened at the same location (lsoa_code) and at the same time (month)
  2. The second cell does the same for firearm incidents.
  3. The third cell joins the tables from the first two cells to obtain the number of drug and firearm incidents that happened at the same location (lsoa_code) and at the same time (month).

The drug_counts and firearm_counts were vectorized, and spearman [32] and pearson [31] correlation was computed between them.

In [41]:
%%time
# filtering out drug offences from all crimes and counting the number of drug offences that happened at the 
# same place (lsoa_code) at the same time (month)
all_crimes.createOrReplaceTempView("all_crimes_table")
drug_offences.createOrReplaceTempView("drug_offences_table")
drug_counts = spark.sql('''
select 
  month,
  lsoa_code,
  count(*) as drug_count
from 
  drug_offences_table
group by
  month, 
  lsoa_code
''')

# dropping nulls if any
drug_counts = drug_counts.na.drop("any")

# showing first 20 rows of drug_offences dataframe
drug_counts.show(truncate=False)

In [42]:
%%time
# filtering firearm incidents from all crimes and counting the number of firearm incidents that happened at the 
# same place (lsoa_code) at the same time (month)
firearm_incidents.createOrReplaceTempView("firearm_incidents_table")
firearm_counts = spark.sql('''
select
  month,
  lsoa_code,
  count(*) as fire_count
from 
  firearm_incidents_table
group by
  month, 
  lsoa_code
''')

# dropping nulls if any
firearm_counts = firearm_counts.na.drop("any")

%%time
# joining drug offences counts and firearm incidents counts that happend at the same place (lsoa_code) at the same time (month)
drug_counts.createOrReplaceTempView("drug_counts_table")
firearm_counts.createOrReplaceTempView("firearm_counts_table")
drug_fire = spark.sql(''' 
select 
  drug_count,
  fire_count
from 
  drug_counts_table as dct
  inner join firearm_counts_table as fct on dct.month = fct.month and dct.lsoa_code = fct.lsoa_code
''')

These correlations were visualized using heatmap because by-default the computed correlations were just numbers and it was not clear exactly which two variables these numbers corresponded to, but heatmap made it visually much more appealing by countering this issue.

Spearman and Pearson correlation resulted in correlation coefficeints of 0.13 and 0.14 respecitively, this means that there is a slight tendency for an increase in one type of incident/offence to be associated with a corresponding increase in the other type of incident/offence, but the relationship is very weak. This indicates that drug offences are not associated with firearm incidents, disproving claim 3.

6. DETAILED ANALYSIS AND CONSIDERATION OF THE APPROPRIATENESS OF THE SOLUTION FOR THE INITIAL PROBLEM¶

The disadvantage of using polynomial regression was that it was prone to overfit with higher degree polynomials and to underfit with lower degree polynomials. Moving average uses mean which makes it sensitive to outliers and both polynomial regression and moving average overlook the complex relationships in data by approximating them. With barplot sometimes it can be challenging to interpret the trend if the rate of change in crime counts is relatively small. Amongst all the visualisations, KDE plot seemed most appropriate for visualizing trend because it comes with an advantage of forecasting the joint probability density/trend for future months and unlike other visualisations it is not sensitive to outliers and does not approximates or overlooks complex relationships in the original time series data. It's only limitation can be that it can be slightly difficult to interpret because it is a top view of a 3D bell curve.

Random forest and GBDT performed similarly. They were significantly better than SARIMAX both in terms of time taken and Normalised RMSE, possibly because tree-based models make no assumptions about the data, unlike SARIMAX which assumes multiplicative seasonality (whereas given time series had additive seasonality) and stationarity and involves a lot of time to find optimal values for the parameters. Making time series stationary by lagging and double differencing creates nulls, which when dropped leads to loss of data, as a consequence of which SARIMAX was trained on less data as compared to tree based models. It was also infered that, since, finally the trained SARIMAX model was to be evaluated using RMSE, instead of AIC, the optimal values of order and seasonal order should have been searched for which the RMSE is the least. This is why a lot of combinations which had low AIC score were resulting in much higher RMSE than combinations with higher AIC score. Tree based models were made to learn the dependency between the previous 12 time steps but the limitation of doing this was that now, the trained model could only forecast 1 future value at a time. Random Forest learns by bootstrapping the training data which disrupts the time dependency structure [23] which is why it resulted in higher RMSE than GBDT. Overall, GBDT was the best model for this use case as it had the least RMSE but it's disadvantage is that it can be influenced by outliers [27], which will have larger residuals and cause the model to focus disproportionately on those points.

From section 3.5 it can be observed that latitude, longitude and lsoa_code all had same number of nulls. Using trimmed postcodes as region indicator would have involved more queries to make joins for replacing latitude and longitude which would account for additional computational cost and possibly more nulls which when dropped, could result in loss of data which is why postcodes approach was not implemented. Thefore, lsoa_city column was used as the region indicator for verifying claim 2 as it was already present in the firearm_incidents dataframe, was associated with the geography column in the lsoa dataframe, had the same number of nulls as the latitude and longitude columns and allowed for larger areas to be considered when summing up total residents and counting firearm incidents.

Using lsoa_code as a location indicator for claim 3 was better than latitude and longitude as it accounts for the same area and requires less computation cost due to involving fewer columns in grouping data and joining tables. Scatter plot could only show the direction of relationship/association and is not good at visualising the strength of especially non-linear relationships which is why it was not implemented. Whereas, correlation can also involve monotonic relationships using ranked values to quantify both the direction and the degree/strength to which two variables are related. Therefore, correlation made more sense to find association between drug offences and firearm incidents. The main drawback/limitation of correlation is that it cannot tell us which variable was the source of the association and which one was the effect. Even when it informs us that there is a relation, it omits to explain why it exists.

7. EVALUATION AND CONCLUSION¶

Based on multiple visualisations and machine learning methods, it is concluded that violent crimes are increasing, but the trend has been almost stable from 2019 to 2021 due to COVID-19 and less aggression by the police [33,34].

Using the LSOA approach, which was better than the postcodes approach both in terms of computational cost and generating larger area, it was concluded that claim 2 was wrong and "City of London" had the highest firearm incidents per head in the UK, despite Birmingham having the most firearm incidents. The possible reason for this can be the concentration of people and resources in "City of London". Additionally, socio-economic factors, such as the huge gap between the rich and the poor in London as compared to any other place in UK can also account for this research finding.

Pearson and Spearman correlations which resulted in correlation co-efficients of 0.14 and 0.13 respectively, were utilised to analyse the relationship between firearm incidents and drug offences, and it was concluded that they are not associated, disproving claim 3. There could be other factors that are contributing to both types of offenses which needs to be further researched.

The results of this investigation make it very evident that violent crimes are on the rise. To prevent this trend from continuing in future, the police should concentrate on repeat victims, high volume criminals, and firearm hotspots identified (in section 5.5 of this research) in order to stop this trend from continuing. Goverment should limit access to firearms which can also help to reduce the number of violent crimes committed with guns. Police should work closely with community members to identify and address potential sources of crime and conflict which can help to build trust between the police and the community, which will make it more likely that people will report crimes and cooperate with investigations. Finally, the police should give priority to instances that result in the greatest amount of harm while making sure that attempts to lower demand do not have any unintended negative effects on the general public.
